It is the one rifle that can emphatically serve multiple functions with ease, be it close quarters or long range. Lightweight and compact, the QR2 packs a punch and delivers uncompromising Robar reliability and accuracy. The QR2 features a Monte-Carlo style ambidextrous stock with a built-in ergonomic palm swell, rear sling swivel stud and a short accessory rail in the beavertail style forend. Robar's NP3 finish is an electroless nickel-based finish for steel, stainless steel and aluminum alloys that co-deposits sub-micron particles of PTFE (polytetrafluoroethylene), otherwise known as Teflon, with electroless nickel. NP3 metal finish offers many benefits. It permits firing for longer periods of time between cleaning, dirt and powder residue have no wet or oily surface to cling to. NP3 is very corrosion resistant and provides a high lubricity and low friction co-efficient, greatly increasing the life expectancy of a firearm due to reduced friction wear. The technicians at The Robar Companies, Inc. have developed a procedure to apply a polymer coating to firearms. POLYMAX offers a number of advantages: Chemical Resistant, Water Resistant, Excellent Adhesion, Mar & Abrasion Resistant, Excellent Hardness & Great Impact Resistance.

title: For Sale/Trade:  RARE INTERDYNAMIC KG-9 (LEGAL PRE KG-9 BAN)
postcontent:
Classified a machine gun by ATF. NO CLASS 3 Needed! (legal to own pre-ban)

The Interdynamic KG9 pistol was made in Miami Florida for a short time in the 1981-82 timeframe by Interdynamic of America, Inc. ATF decided in January 1982 that the gun was too easy to convert into a machine gun, and therefore decided that an unmodified open bolt semi-auto KG-9 was a machine gun. ATF exempted unmodified semi-auto KG-9 pistols made before this ruling from the scope of the ruling, so there are so-called grandfathered KG-9 pistols available in the USA. The KG-9 was based on a Swedish designed machine pistol, the MP-9. After the ATF ruling the gun was redesigned into a closed bolt, striker fired pistol, the Interdynamic KG-99, which was sold in the 1982-83 timeframe. After that Interdynamic went out of buisness.

The original gun the cheap tec-9 was made to copy. Rare! Less than 1000 made! Look it up. 

I will trade for handguns too. There is a hairline crack in the bottom. It still works/shoots fine. Here is a video go the gun for sale http://youtu.be/3iUc8hX2938

title: For Sale:  WARNING: MISR90 is not a "Maadi"
postcontent:
Seller on here is trying to pass off a CAI (century arms international) MISR90 as a "Maadi" AKM.  This rifle was made from a Maadi receiver and a Chinese MAK90 parts kit.  Rifles built with 1mm receivers and parts kits meant for 1.5mm receivers are no good.  Look at the furniture!  It is MAK90 furniture, and the handguards are Chinese blond wood and are smooth (nothing to grip).  Real Maadi AKM rifles have the "palm swell" handguards (which provides something better to grip the rifle).  Don't believe me, then google Chinese and Egyptian AKM handguards.

BUYER BEWARE.  SELLER SHOULD BE ASHAMED FOR LYING.  His ad persistently advertises the rifle as a "Maadi" when the seller probably knows the truth about his AKM: frankenstein build from the monkies at CAI.

title: For Sale:   Smith & Wesson Model 610-3 "used"
postcontent:
The Model 610 is a six-shot, double-action revolver chambered for the 10mm Auto cartridge first created for the Bren Ten pistol. It is manufactured by Smith & Wesson. It uses the N-frame, similar to the Smith & Wesson Model 29 in .44 Magnum, and the Model 28 in .357 Magnum. Since the 10mm Auto is a rimless automatic pistol cartridge, moon clips are used to hold cartridges when loading and extracting spent cases en bloc. Since the .40 Smith & Wesson is a shorter, less powerful variant of the 10mm Auto but has the same diameter, the Model 610 can also chamber and fire .40 Smith & Wesson rounds.

This is a used model rated at 98% comes in the original box but has no moon clips with it.  Photo is of the actual firearm.
